occurrences.line_text: Hath not enough, but wants in greatest store;
Through long enprisonment, and hard constraint,
Whereat he wondred much, and gan enquere,
Of whom she gan enquire of her estate.
Of whom he gan enquire his cause of dread;
So towardes them they coasted, to enquire
And gan enquire of him, with mylder mood,
She for that yron prison did enquire,
Then Artegall gan of the Prince enquire,
Of whom Sir Artegall gan then enquire
The matrone stayd no lenger to enquire,
And hauing long beheld, at last enquired
And did in stocke of earthly flesh enrace,
With heauenly gifts from heuen first enraced?
Therewith enrag'd she loudly gan to bray,
But he enrag'd with rancor, nothing heares.
Wherewith he all enrag'd, these bitter speaches said.
Who all enrag'd with smart and franticke yre,
And hellish fury all enragd, I sought
Wherewith enrag'd she fiercely at them flew,
Greatly he grew enrag'd, and furiously
Yet therewith sore enrag'd, with sterne regard
He all enrag'd, his shiuering speare did shake,
Of that sad stroke, that halfe enrag'd she grew,
But rather more enrag'd for those words sake;
Wherewith the beast enrag'd to loose his pray,
And harts of great Hero's doest enrage,
And euill meanes, with which she doth enrage
And halfe enraged at her shamelesse guise,
Pardon the errour of enraged wight,
And threw it to the ground, enraged rife,
The cruell wound enraged him so sore,
What heauens? what altars? what enraged heates
Therewith all suddeinly he seemd enraged,
And all enraged, thus him loudly shent;
Outragiously, as they enraged were,
Had them enraged with fell surquedry;
The aged Dame him seeing so enraged,
The more was Claribell enraged rife
Streight downe she ranne, like an enraged cow,
But he the more thereby enraged was,
With that the wyld man more enraged grew,
Beheld, eftsoones he all enraged grew,
He ran at him enrag[e]d in stead of being frayde.
And halfe enraged at that ruefull sight;
Like a fell mastiffe through enraging heat,
Had so enranckled her malitious hart,
With diuers trees, enrang'd in euen rankes;
In manner of a maske, enranged orderly.
Beholds her Nymphes, enraung'd in shadie wood,
One might haue seene enraung'd disorderly,
Three ranckes of yron teeth enraunged were,
With deadly rancour he enraunged fond,
And were enraunged ready, still for fight.
In endlesse rancks along enraunged were,
Where, as this day I was enraunging it,
Which doe the earth enrich and beautifie:
Now therefore, if thou wilt enriched bee,
And him enriched through the ouerthrow
The which mote haue enriched all vs heare.
So lauishly enricht with natures threasure,
And made a griesly wound in his enriuen side.
Enrold in flames, and smouldring dreriment,
Enrold in duskish smoke and brimstone blew;
Immortall fame for euer hath enrold;
Came rushing in the fomy waues enrold,
Of her immortall wombe, to be in heauen enrold.
Her faire lockes in rich circlet be enrold,
A famous history to be enrold
Glistring like gold, amongst the plights enrold,
Mongst rocks and caues, where she enrold doth lie
And to enroll thy memorable name,
For which enrolled is your glorious name
And eke enrooted deepe must be that Tree,
For hast did ouer-runne, in dust enrould,
That doth this Redcrosse knights ensample plainly proue.
And made ensample of their mournefull sight
That of his puissance proud ensample made;
This dayes ensample hath this lesson deare
Ensample make of him your haplesse ioy,
He shewd that day, and rare ensample made,
Ill by ensample good doth often gayne.
And shewst th'ensa[m]ple of thy childish might,
And henceforth by this dayes ensample trow,
And laid forth for ensample of the best:
How they themselues doe thine ensample make,
Did follow that ensample, which he blam'd afore.
Ensample be of mind intemperate,
Ensample of his wondrous faculty,
And braue ensample, both of martiall,
But by ensample of the last dayes losse,
Shall of him selfe a braue ensample shew,
Late dayes ensample, which these eyes beheld,
Therefore faire Infant her ensample make
Ne doest by others death ensample take,
The warlike Maid, th'ensample of that might,
To make ensample of his heauenly grace,
To youre faire selues a faire ensample frame,
That Ladies all may follow her ensample dead.
So straunge ensample of conception;
To be th'ensample of true loue alone,
But neuer let th'ensample of the bad
And makes ensample of mans wretched state,
But yet that nights ensample did bewray,
And of faire Britomart ensample take,
Next Hercules his like ensample shewed,
By like ensample mote for euer warned bee.
Seeing that sad ensample them before,
By late ensample of that courteous deed,
And by the like ensample warned bee,
Ensample take of Mirabellaes case,
Hauing escapt so sad ensamples in his sight.
Thus said; Behold th'ensamples in our sights,
Forreine ensamples, it to haue exprest?
And bounteous Trent, that in him selfe enseames
And good successes, which their foes ensew:
Or other secret vertue did ensew;
And next to him Iocante did ensew;
But with like fiercenesse did ensew the chace:
They loued armes, and knighthood did ensew,
Of dainty musicke, which did next ensew
So hauing sayd, the younger did ensew;
To proue if better foote then horsebacke would ensew.
For doubtlesse death ensewd, if any him descryde.
Ensewd, whose noyance fild the fearefull sted,
Then next ensew'd the Paragon to see
Strooke through his shoulder, that the blood ensew'd
To whom she thus; but ere her words ensewed,
Of high displeasure, that ensewen might,
Th'ill to preuent, that life ensewen may.
But you, faire Sir, whose pageant next ensewes,
Ensewing, made her knowen to him at last:
They in awayt would closely him ensnarle,
Where what ensu'd, shall in next Canto be begonne.
That nature had for wantonesse ensude
How many mischieues should ensue his heedlesse hast.
Wayting what would ensue of that euent.
Whom straight the Prince ensuing, in together far'd.
Late learnd what harme to hastie trust ensu'th,
And all that gentle noriture ensu'th:
And thicke entangled knots adown does slacke.
All bard with golden bendes, which were entayld
The mortall steele despiteously entayld
A worke of rich entayle, and curious mould,
That darkesome caue they enter, where they find
Such is the state of men: thus enter wee
On which it seizing, no way enter might,
To enter in, and reape the dew reward:
Should euer enter in his bounteous thought,
To enter into that same balefull Bowre,
Is suffred here to enter, but he seeme
So as he was not let to enter there:
The wood they enter, and search euery where,
And watcht, that none should enter nor issew;
To enter in, but found it locked fast:
Yet many waies to enter may be found,
Full many did affray, that else faine enter would.
To enter in, or issue forth below:
Which way he enter might, without endangerment.
Did beat vppon the gates to enter in,
Made them all enter in before her sight,
All arm'd to point, and first the Lists did enter:
Did enter in, ne would that night depart;
Pelmell with them attonce did enter in.
Or good direction, how to enter in,
Did enter in, and slew the Porter on the flore.
He durst not enter into th'open greene,
Those keyes, and made himselfe free enterance.
The whiles were enterchaunged twixt them two;
To treat with her by way of enterdeale,
First entering, the dreadfull Mage there found
When armes he swore, and streight did enterpris
And to the beast gan turne his enterprise;
From first to last in your late enterprise,
Equall vnto this haughtie enterprise?
And passing Dee with hardy enterprise,
That in all glory and great enterprise,
Before ye enterprise that way to wend:
Mote him befall vpon new enterprise;
I am the wrong'd, whom ye did enterprise
Hastily bent, that enterprise to heare,
As bent to some malicious enterprise,
And passed forth, to follow his first enterprise.
Then enterprised prayse for dread to disauaunce.
Haue enterprizd that Monster to subdew;
And with him sixe knights more, which enterpriz'd
And dayly how through hardy enterprize,
Him at the threshold met, and well did enterprize.
Withdraw from thought of warlike enterprize,
Since he this hardie enterprize began:
How to effect so hard an enterprize,
That for her sake refus'd to enterprize
That enterprize, for greatest glories gayne.
How she that Ladies libertie might enterprize.
That we may compasse this our enterprize?
Prince Arthur takes the enterprize
Which ye haue had in your late enterprize.
He could him force to loose, or leaue his enterprize.
And valiant knights doe rashly enterprize,
Which durst her dreaded reskue enterprize,
Asham'd to thinke, how he that enterprize,
Goodly she entertaind those noble knights,
Where they were entertaind with curteous
And Panope her entertaind eke well,
Where he with cruell warre was entertaind
But entertaind him in so rude a wise,
Goodly they all that knight do entertaine,
The guiltlesse man with guile to entertaine?
With louely court he gan her entertaine;
Those for Gods sake his dewty was to entertaine.
Him goodly greetes, and faire does entertaine,
And entertaine themselues with court'sies meet,
Seemely to entertaine her new-come guest,
As feates of armes, and loue to entertaine,
New merth, her passenger to entertaine:
Proffer thy giftes, and fitter seruaunts entertaine.
But were your will, her sold to entertaine,
The whiles, the Faerie knight did entertaine
The loue of women not to entertaine;
Where she was wont her Sprights to entertaine
That thing of course he counted, loue to entertaine.
And pleasing toyes he would her entertaine,
They had as then her long to entertaine.)
And entertaine with her occasions sly,
Then his foes loue or liking entertaine:
Then termes to entertaine of common guize,
Ne for aduantage terme to entertaine,
That none should dare him once to entertaine:
Most ioyfully she them did entertaine,
To weet which way were best to entertaine,
As to them seemed fit time to entertaine.
This wize did they each other entertaine,
How each to entertaine with curt'sie well beseene,
Therein he them full faire did entertaine
With idle hopes, which them doe entertaine,
During which time he did her entertaine
With better tearmes she did him entertaine;
Both whom they goodly well did entertaine;
And entertained them right fairely, as befell.
Him long she so with shadowes entertained,
And entertained her the best he might
Ne looke for entertainement, where none was:
His office was to giue entertainement
Their goodly entertainement and great glee:
As comely carriage, entertainement kynde,
Her vildly entertaines, and will or nill,
And entertaines with comely courteous glee,
And entertaines with friendly chearefull mood.
And entertaining her with curt'sies meet,
Such entertainment base, ne ought would eat,
Him to receiue with entertainment meete.
And with more myld aspect those two to entertake.
And entertaynd them both, as best became,
Her entertaynd; nath'lesse she inly deemd
Mote not be entertaynd, as seemed meet,
Them fairely entertaynd with curt'sies meete,
With tryumph entertayn'd and glorifyde,
Them entertayn'd, fit for their dignities,
Him entertayn'd, and did her champion chose:
Bad them not looke for better entertayne;
But after all her princely entertayne,
But she in gentle wise me entertayned,
With her vnworthy knight, who ill him entertayned.
Where him Blandina fayrely entertayned,
And entertayning them with courage stout,
Whose bounches hanging downe, seemed to entice
But there it present was, and did fraile sense entice.
Then backe to fight againe, new breathed and entire.
It framed was, one massie entire mould,
(Entire affection hateth nicer hands)
What doe I recke, sith that he dyde entire?
Who with entire affection him receau'd,
And ransackt all her veines with passion entire.
And like a shadow wexe, whiles with entire
He ween'd that his affection entire
Ioying his loue in likenesse more entire;
When first he loued her with heart entire,
From his false eyes, into their harts and parts entire.
But most she touched was with griefe entire,
And in them bore true louers vowes entire:
She entred into all the partes entire.
And him embracing twixt his armes entire,
But with entire affection and appearaunce plaine.
Was touched with compassion entire,
And groning sore from grieued hart entire,
And gan to highest God entirely pray,
Your countrey kin, and you entirely pray
Yet nothing could him to impatience entise.
And thence him forward led, him further to entise.
And all, that might his melting hart entise
With which thou canst euen Ioue himselfe to loue entise.
That trauellers to him seemd to entize;
And friends to termes of gentle truce entize,
That here in Ladies lap entombed art,
But be entombed in the rauen or the kight?
By which he lyes entombed solemnly.
So now entombed lyes at Stoneheng by the heath.
Where late his treasure he entombed had,
Were stretcht now forth at length without entraile.
Which he from hellish entrailes did expire.
That all mine entrailes flow with poysnous gore,
And for her entrailes made an open way,
And his whot fire burnes in mine entrails bright,
And in their entrails, full of quicke Brimston,
Asswage the fury, which his entrails teares:
Out of her poysnous entrails, fraught with dire decay.
Compared to the creatures in the seas entrall.
Sucking the seas into his entralles deepe,
Weening their wonted entrance to haue found
Dame Vna, wearie Dame, and entrance did requere.
That readie entrance was not at his call:
Cald Maluen, who entrance none denide:
By that same hole an entrance darke and bace
The stroke thereof from entrance may defend;
Was to them doen, their entrance to forstall,
Who gently answered, They entrance did desire.
That neuer entrance any durst pretend,
He nought was moued at their entrance bold:
Of readie entrance, which ought euermore
Whereat soft knocking, entrance he desyrd.
Like as the rest, late entrance deare besought;
For flatly he of entrance was refusd,
That at the last he found a caue with entrance small.
More easie issew now, then entrance late
He at his entrance charg'd his powrefull speare
From fearefull cowards, entrance to forstall,
But Hatred would my entrance haue restrayned,
In entrance, did me also friend in my retrate.
Of whom he entrance sought, but was denide,
The whiles the Prince there kept the entrance still:
Yet could the Seneschals no entrance find
To see if entrance there as yet obtaine he might.
And tryde all waies, how each mote entrance make
Vnto the entrance ran: where the bold knight
With cunning traines him to entrap vnwares.
Had him betidde, or hidden daunger did entrap.
Misfortune waites aduantage to entrap
Him to entrap vnwares another way he wist.
For whom he could not kill, he practizd to entrap.
Awayting to entrap the warelesse wight,
who seekes her to entrap.
Sometime least his false foe did him entrap
Ne yet entrap in treasons subtill traine.
Then to entrap him by false treacherie:
Hypocrisie him to entrappe,
Entrapped slew, and brought to shamefull graue.
But now entrapt of loue, which him betrayd,
Here may ye not haue entraunce, though we would:
And entraunce crau'd, which was denied erst.
They battred day and night, and entraunce did awate.
Out of his dreame, that did him long entraunce,
Though nought beleu'd, & entrau[n]ce late did not refuse.
And dreadfull horrour did all entraunce choke,
And seeking often entraunce, afterwards in vaine.
That stopt the entraunce with his spacious stride,
They pressed forward, entraunce to haue made.
And entraunce wonne. Streight th'other fled away,
Did choke the entraunce with a lumpe of sin,
And entraunce boldly vnto him forbad.
He lost himselfe, and like one halfe entraunced grew.
In a rich Iewell, and therein entrayld
His pricking armes, entrayld with roses red,
With wanton yuie twyne entrayld athwart,
And round about a border was entrayld,
Entrayled mutually in louely lore,
His inward parts, and all his entrayles wast,
Her inward brest, and in her entrayles fryde,
And of her owne foule entrayles makes her meat;
And all the secrets of their entrayles sought.
Does faire entreat; no courting nicetie,
Her selfe to shroud, and pleasures to entreat.
But for this carkasse pardon I entreat,
The Lady did faire Britomart entreat,
Words fearen babes. I meane not thee entreat
Then with dishonorable termes her to entreat.
Nay let vs first (said Satyrane[)] entreat
As seemed by their semblaunt did entreat;
And euermore, when he did grace entreat,
To better termes of myldnesse did entreat,
Mote we entreat you, sith this gentle crew
And gan entreat that iron man below,
And him entreat for grace, that had procur'd her paine.
She chang'd that threatfull mood, & mildly gan entreat.
And humbly gan that mightie Queene entreat,
Gan him entreat euen with submission base,
Ne ought it mote auaile her to entreat
For aye the more, that she did them entreat,
Doth to his home entreate.
She doth subdue, she fowly doth entreate.
So all the twenty I likewise entreated,
And earnestly entreated that they might
With faire entreatie and sweet blandishment,
Nor no entreatie to his loue be led;
And try if thou by faire entreatie, can
By whose entreatie both they ouercommen,
Ne Ladies loues, ne sweete entreaties might
But his hard rocky hart for no entreating
And fowle entreaty him indignifyde,
And myld entreaty lodging did for her beseeke.
Faire harbour that them seemes; so in they entred arre.
Into the Castle entred forcibly,
Where entred in, his foot could find no flore,
But entred in a spacious court they see,
Yet being entred, might not backe retyre;
Soone as he entred was, the dore streight way
Aswell their entred guestes to keepe within,
Thus being entred, they behold around
The Damzell there arriuing entred in;
The whiles the Championesse now entred has
So soone as she was entred, round about
Then entred Cambell first into the list,
That through the mayles into his thigh it entred,
Till that there entred on the other side,
Euen as he ready was there to haue entred,
So as I entred, I did backeward looke,
Who being entred, nought did then auaile
There entred in, he round about him saw
She entred into all the partes entire.
There as they entred at the Scriene, they saw
The other which was entred, laboured fast
Of that was doen, and entred in a rout.
Entrenched deepe with knife accursed keene,
In strong entrenchments he did closely place,
That erst all entrers wont so cruelly to scorch.
And entring is; when that disdainfull beast
The knight and Vna entring, faire her greet,
The knights there entring, did him reuerence dew
Right as he entring was into the flood,
Streight entring into Triamond, him fild
There entring in, they found the goodman selfe,
Sir Scudamour there entring, much admired
And entring in, found none therein abide,
By her I entring halfe dismayed was,
The cry whereof entring the hollow caue,
There whilest they entring, th'one did th'other stay,
But Calidore in th'entry close did stand,
So long till all the entry was with bodies mand.
Reproch sharpe stings, Repentance whips entwind,
Entyced her, to him for to accord.
Pyrrochles was, and grieued eke entyre;
And there out sucking venime to her parts entyre.
Would haue embraced her with hart entyre.
Or deepe emboweld in the earth entyre:
And liued long in peace and loue entyre,
And softly whispering him, entyrely prayd,
That of her loue he was entyrely seized,
With which he fed her fancie, and entysd
Whose luring baytes oftimes doe heedlesse harts entyse.
And all those ioyes that weake mankind entyse.
Entyst the Boy, as well that art she knew,
Was vnderneath enueloped with gold,
And heauens chearefull face enueloped,
Is in a noyous cloud enueloped,
That was with gold and Ermines faire enueloped.
And on his shield enueloped seuenfold
But that enuenimd sting, the which of yore,
And hurt far off vnknowne, whom euer she enuide.
That euen Nature selfe enuide the same,
Gainst Blandamour, whom alwaies he enuide:
And then both Knights enuide, & Ladies eke did spight.
Ne any left, that victorie to him enuide.
And next to him malicious Enuie rode,
Such one vile Enuie was, that fift in row did sitt.
They enuie her in their malitious mind,
Ne wicked enuie, ne vile gealosy
Each other does enuie with deadly hate,
And enuie base, to barke at sleeping fame:
But fierce Cundah gan shortly to enuie
Let later age that noble vse enuie,
Full of great enuie and fell gealosy,
But if the heauens did his dayes enuie,
Each bird his mate, ne any does enuie
His hart with secret enuie gan to swell,
Whereat the rest gan greatly to enuie:
But for that many did that shield enuie,
Her name was Enuie, knowen well thereby;
For what so Enuie good or bad did fynd,
Was neare to Enuie, euen her neighbour next;
And Enuie first, as she that first him eyde,
That certes I your happinesse enuie,
Yet Paridell him enuied therefore,
Each others equall puissaunce enuies,
Through enuies snares or fortunes freakes vnkind:
Prouokt with VVrath, and Enuies false surmise,
Braue moniments remaine, which yet that land enuies.
All those were lawlesse lustes, corrupt enuies,
Which he to shun, and stop vile enuies sting,
Fearlesse of fortunes chaunge or enuies dread,
But enuies cloud still dimmeth vertues ray.
Coridon enuies him, yet he
That enuies louers long prosperity,
Full enuious that night so long his roome did fill.
He to him leapt, and that same enuious gage
That of no enuious eyes he mote be spyde:
Most enuious man, that grieues at neighbours good,
Whiles nothing enuious nature them forth throwes
So puissant foe, with enuious despight
Those pretious hils from straungers enuious sight,
Another seemed enuious, or coy,
And enuious of Vncles soueraintie,
